{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611765"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:15:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:15:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16242"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16242"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.46,0.04,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8933"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115387"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8933"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16242"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97390"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"563"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"7575"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"10654"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21261"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115387"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe neonatal skull has unique characteristics that facilitate passage through the birth canal during delivery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the adaptation of neonatal skull bones during vaginal delivery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calvarial bones overlap at suture lines","Fontanelles temporarily close","Skull bones fuse together","Cranial bones become more mineralised","Suture lines permanently widen"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe calvarial bones, which include the frontal, parietal, and occipital bones, are not fully fused at birth. Instead, they are connected by sutures (fibrous joints) and fontanelles (soft spots) that allow flexibility and movement. During vaginal delivery, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalvarial bones overlap at suture lines\u003C/strong\u003E in a process called molding. This temporary displacement allows the head to pass through the birth canal. The unfused nature of neonatal skull bones and presence of sutures and fontanelles makes this possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFontanelles temporarily close\u003C/strong\u003E during delivery would actually hinder the molding process, as fontanelles remain open to allow for molding and brain growth. \u003Cstrong\u003ESkull bones fuse together\u003C/strong\u003E would prevent the necessary flexibility, as the bones actually remain separate to allow movement. \u003Cstrong\u003ECranial bones become more mineralised\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur during delivery, as mineralisation does not change during this process. \u003Cstrong\u003ESuture lines permanently widen\u003C/strong\u003E would be problematic for skull integrity, whereas any changes to suture lines during delivery are temporary. After delivery, the skull bones gradually return to their normal positions over several days. The fontanelles and sutures remain open to accommodate rapid brain growth during infancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["During birth, unfused calvarial bones can overlap at suture lines to allow passage through the birth canal.","The flexibility of the neonatal skull is an important adaptation that facilitates normal vaginal delivery.","Cranial molding is temporary and resolves within days after birth."],"references":["Romero R, Espinoza J, Kusanovic JP, Gotsch F, Hassan S, Erez O, Chaiworapongsa T, Mazor M. The preterm parturition syndrome. BJOG. 2006 Dec;113 Suppl 3(Suppl 3):17-42. doi: 10.1111/j.1471-0528.2006.01120.x. Erratum in: BJOG. 2008 Apr;115(5):674-5. PMID: 17206962; PMCID: PMC7062298.","Heyborne KD. A Systematic Review of Intrapartum Fetal Head Compression: What Is the Impact on the Fetal Brain? AJP Rep. 2017 Apr;7(2):e79-e85. doi: 10.1055/s-0037-1602658. PMID: 28465865; PMCID: PMC5406232.","Dosman CF, Andrews D, Goulden KJ. Evidence-based milestone ages as a framework for developmental surveillance. Paediatr Child Health. 2012 Dec;17(10):561-8. doi: 10.1093/pch/17.10.561. PMID: 24294064; PMCID: PMC3549694.","Sheldrick RC, Schlichting LE, Berger B, Clyne A, Ni P, Perrin EC, Vivier PM. Establishing New Norms for Developmental Milestones. Pediatrics. 2019 Dec;144(6):e20190374. doi: 10.1542/peds.2019-0374. Epub 2019 Nov 14. PMID: 31727860; PMCID: PMC6889967.","Lissauer, T., \u0026 Carroll, W. (Eds.). (2021). Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book: Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97390"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16242"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97390"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T14:28:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T14:29:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8933"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115387"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gro